msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:51
#, no-c-format
msgid "Running a Single Command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Logged in as normal user, you can run any command as &rootuser; by adding "
"&sudo; before it. It will prompt for the root password and, if authenticated "
"successfully, run the command as &rootuser;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:57
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"&prompt.user;<command>id -un</command><co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.id\"/>\n"
"tux\n"
"&prompt.sudo;<command>id -un</command>\n"
"root's password:<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.pw\"/>\n"
"root\n"
"&prompt.user;<command>id -un</command>\n"
"tux<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.after\"/>\n"
"&prompt.sudo;<command>id -un</command>\n"
"<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.nopw\"/>\n"
"root\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:71
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <command>id -un</command> command prints the login name of the current "
"user."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:77
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The password is not shown during input, neither as clear text nor as bullets."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:83
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Only commands started with &sudo; are run with elevated privileges. If you "
"run the same command without the &sudo; prefix, it is run with the "
"privileges of the current user again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:90
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For a limited amount of time, you do not need to enter the &rootuser; "
"password again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:97
#, no-c-format
msgid "I/O Redirection"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:98
#, no-c-format
msgid "I/O redirection does not work as you would probably expect:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:101
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"&prompt.sudo;echo s &gt; /proc/sysrq-trigger\n"
"bash: /proc/sysrq-trigger: Permission denied\n"
"&prompt.sudo;cat &lt; /proc/1/maps\n"
"bash: /proc/1/maps: Permission denied\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:107
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Only the <command>echo</command> / <command>cat</command> binary is run with "
"elevated privileges, while the redirection is performed by the user's shell "
"with user privileges. You can either start a shell like in <xref linkend="
"\"sec.sudo.shell\"/> or use the <command>dd</command> utility instead:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:114
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"echo s | sudo dd of=/proc/sysrq-trigger\n"
"sudo dd if=/proc/1/maps | cat <!-- TODO: Better example! -->\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:122
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting a Shell"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:123
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Having to add &sudo; before every command can be cumbersome. While you could "
"specify a shell as a command <command>sudo bash</command> , it is "
"recommended to rather use one of the built-in mechanisms to start a shell:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:130
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>sudo -s (&lt;command&gt;)</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:133
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Starts a shell specified by the <envar>SHELL</envar> environment variable or "
"the target user's default shell. If a command is given, it is passed to the "
"shell (with the <option>-c</option> option), else the shell is run in "
"interactive mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:139
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>sudo -i\n"
"root's password:\n"
"<prompt>root:/home/tux # </prompt>exit\n"
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:148
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>sudo -i (&lt;command&gt;)</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:151
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Like <option>-s</option> , but starts the shell as login shell. This means "
"that the shell's start-up files ( <filename>.profile</filename> etc.) are "
"processed and the current working directory is set to the target user's home "
"directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:157
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>sudo -i\n"
"root's password:\n"
"<prompt>root:~ # </prompt>exit\n"
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:169
#, no-c-format
msgid "Environment Variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:170
#, no-c-format
msgid "By default, &sudo; does not propagate environment variables:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:173
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"&prompt.user;ENVVAR=test env | grep ENVVAR\n"
"ENVVAR=test\n"
"&prompt.user;ENVVAR=test sudo env | grep ENVVAR\n"
"root's password:\n"
"<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.env.novar\"/>\n"
"&prompt.user;\n"
"      "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:183
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The empty output shows that the environment variable <envar>ENVVAR</envar> "
"did not exist in the context of the command run with &sudo;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:190
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This behavior can be changed by the <literal>env_reset</literal> option, see "
"<xref linkend=\"tab.adm.sudo.options\"/> ."
msgstr ""

